      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Yoram Hazony (Op-Ed, June 13) bewails ''the shift in the political mood of Israeli Arabs,'' who increasingly identify as Palestinians rather than Israelis.</p>
        <p>Has Mr. Hazony given any thought to how Jews would identify themselves if they lived as a minority in a country that singled them out for second-class citizenship, deprived them of equal access to state financing and services, and excluded them from the dominant majority when it came to voting on state issues?</p>
        <p>There are those who would maintain that given Israel's circumstances, these forms of discrimination are unavoidable. But isn't it also unavoidable for victims of such discrimination to feel deeply alienated, and is it surprising that they should identify with three million Palestinians who have been denied national self-determination?</p>
        <p>HENRY SIEGMAN  New York, June 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations.</p>
      </block>
